Inflation in Europe has deteriorated on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, said the European Community Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
The official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, reports Bloomberg.
Unlike US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the guiding interest rate by saying that the fall in interest rates, with the rise in raw materials prices and the decline in unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to maintain the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to an analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we need to discourage" inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this issue later.
In Germany, the rate of inflation of 3.3 per cent has been record over the past 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6% to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has started due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Long-term quota for cereals has increased by 88 per cent and the soya price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
Food oil and milk products prices also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price increased by 52 per cent and last month, a black gold barrel cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 per cent, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent over the next 3 to 4 months.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease the guiding rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of the Fidesz (the Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly in early December, so since 2002, he currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (the Survey Institute) has never previously found such a weak social support, 13 per cent.
For faithful voters, the difference, due to the greatest determination of opposition voters, would represent support of more than two thirds (71 per cent) against the support of a fifth (20 per cent) for MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is 2% throughout the population.
On the faithful voters some to go to the vote, the number of supporters of the two parties increased by 1 per cent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who felt that the economic situation in the country was particularly serious has never been as high, it is 41 per cent and, according to 46 per cent additional, the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic prospects of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects an aggravation and only one tenth expects an improvement in the situation.
