To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to organize next Sunday", only 55 per cent of the surveyed would certainly participate and 15 per cent additional would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be undoubted.
74 per cent of people would say no to registration rights in higher education, 79 per cent would say no to consultation costs and 84 per cent would say no to hospital stay costs.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of the voters would reject the introduction of registration rights, consultation and hospital stay costs.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets implanted in Budaörs' commercial triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, unlike the increase in VAT this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Panier also increased by 16 per cent on average, an increase in value significantly more than a thousand forints in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already flew" in the major food stores last December, did not increase brutally compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked by the fact that goods purchased significantly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Cart in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded 91 forints, at least the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10 573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at the level of last year, but the prices of turkey net, nuts and poppy increased sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to 139 forints only.
Competition did not decrease the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the recorded bottle of two litres of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the recorded bottle included.
It does not prevent that this year, in terms of daily Panier, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the most expensive.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of her daily Cart by 15 per cent, while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 per cent, respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive basket and the most expensive basket this year, we find a 12 percent difference, while the difference between last year's most expensive and last year's most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forks, while knowing that the impact of the increase in VAT rates has already been noticed in the Christmas prices of last year.
This process made trade confused, hypermarkets could not clearly determine the margin applied to products as long as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalcifies the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the level of trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the price increase in the Daily Cart has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was more than 1,630 forints than last year's and the lowest prices also increased by 1,284 forints.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we noticed a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the daily consumer goods prices increased by more than 30 per cent in the hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for certain essential foods, the Institute of Statistics found an increase in prices of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to its daily Cart, this seems almost absurd, since the price level of this product, which was already very expensive last year, has risen by just over 10 per cent from the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to accept the brutal increase in prices by multinationals as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at the prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy in quantity, they take long-contained food by pallets.
Wednesday morning, major queues formed at the tre hypermarkets because the number of customers increased suddenly.
However, according to our information, sales are less important in the province, many multinationals complain from survey companies that they do not even reach the intended sales, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals make savings on disinfectants
This year, more than 1,000 infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The health conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overcrowding of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the Chief Doctor of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also make the economy on disinfectants
Not long ago a MRSA infection was diagnosed in the János Hospital trauma department.
Antimicrobial resistant bacteria was detected in a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person with a serious car accident came out of the hospital, but shortly after he had to return to the hospital due to a MRSA infection and since then the doctors have not been able to do a major surgery with him because of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multiresistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Monitoring System, says Karolina Böröcz, Chief Doctor of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Knowing that it is the number of infections caused by a multiresistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. staphylococcus aureus resistant to meticilline-oxacilline.
A third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, amygdalitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics and are easily healable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria that is well resistant to antibiotics that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly patients, with small weights or with a weak body.
According to János Hospital Director, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily hospitals.
Most importantly, we should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only the one or not looking for it," Tibor Nyulasi said.
SA resists antibiotics.
"These sick people are isolated, the caretaker puts rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics suitable for treating them," Tibor Nyulasi said.
At first, hospitalized patients are examined if they carry MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
The sample is not in mode
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be warned, but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favourable to prevent the development and proliferation of multiresistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs especially in hospitals and in older people's homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate MRSA patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
It must be known that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases occur only if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief doctor at the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in ambulatory and basic care, Karolina Böröcz reported.
Many hospitals make savings on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but there are significant shortcomings in hospitals, too, in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemic, patients should be at least 1.5 metres away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is lower in a detectable way or then the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Governmental project against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA is exorbitant expenditure for social security funds, which is why it is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the impact of MRSAs.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multiresistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
Commissioner, author of a deadly accident, was not drunk
The official finding of the death accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement was drawn up.
It may be excluded that the 22nd arrondissement commissioner, who has since resigned from his position, who has crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led to drunkenness or dizziness, announced on Friday Attila Morvai, spokesperson of the Public Ministry of the Capital after the relevant finding had been established.
