EUR 400 million additional for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed, on Friday in Budapest, three agreements of a total value of EUR 400 million on a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, which has already been signed by the parties on a loan contract worth EUR 100 million. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also covers the budget financing of education-related projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, the remaining EUR 150 million will be used later following the extension of the credit contract.
The parties have signed a EUR 50 million contract for innovation, and the state budget will use this envelope primarily in the framework of the research and development project to be implemented at the University of Debrecen.
In the negotiations, draft line 4 of the metro was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would re-discuss any change to the initial contract when Hungary has completed the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans according to the EURIBOR interest rate, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment commission.
Bulgaria, EU real estate market paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, and the attention of all of Europe is directed to this country of the Balkans which has not been mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought on this EU market that is still the cheapest but who will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max division.
At present, in the real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular destination in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and houses on the cheap seafront.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, at the seaside, Albena, the "Gold Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar, but they are increasingly looking for a building in the region of Kavarna and Balcik.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, early or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also increasingly available to buy in the very cheap area of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, the commercial and office surfaces promise the highest rate of amortisation.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus become a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors already buy in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time seeking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others arrive from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the edge of the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who are planning to settle buy renovated buildings at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old landed houses at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication opportunities, the proximity of a large city, shops and generally the local doctor.
The second group includes secondary residence buyers (since last December, Bulgaria has been quoted among the first 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is composed of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving a medium or long-term surplus.
The price of capital buildings is constantly rising due to increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last five years, they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and six per cent Hungarian
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Water, the meeting of professionals will be completed on Tuesday, but on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians coming from 192 countries of the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define the efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined in the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, there are intense discussions on this issue between developing countries and developed countries.
The United States also indicated that, at the moment, they did not wish to discuss accurate figures, but that they were prepared to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions from 25 to 40 per cent to the 1990 level by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need of such aid, without reducing emissions.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The support fund defined in the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a Board of Directors consisting of 16 members likely under the United Nations Global Environment Fund (GEF), reported Piac es Profit (Market and Profit).
Six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister for the Environment and Waters, reaffirms the EU's ambition to retain its role as an amiral vessel in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to the 1990 level, regardless of the success of the signing of the "After 2012 Agreement", and was ready to reduce them to 30 per cent if the other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibility and capacity.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries signatory to the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 per cent, and all 15 EU members of that time took a 8 per cent less commitment.
Hungary has undertaken to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the period from 1985 to 1987, and our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
The issue is great in Bali because the long-term international climate policy agreement must be implemented over the period of two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In that case, commitments to reduce below the values set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, which was highlighted in the new IPCC report, the international scientific body, which obtained the Nobel Peace Prize, which was responsible for addressing climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army Recruits on YouTube
The British Army units communicate recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video sharing site with a view to becoming popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) who was passionate about YouTube: the special units involved in Afghanistan are loading video sequences on operations against the Taliban since March 2006, announced the BBC.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to Londrès or the landlords load them on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been viewed by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and communicates videos about operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Department (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial goal of the air force, the videos were taken on the net to recruit, and according to the Department of Defence, they were also used to make the real goals of the presence of the army abroad known to the general public.
The propaganda published by this way does not cost anything compared to the usual advertising of recruitment on television, which was communicated to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but also inevitably conveys a political message as it in a special form justifies the soundness of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game
The army is obsessed because, apart from carefully compiled and censored videos, amateur videos have been passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about losses, but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
Furthermore, many videos had already been made on the net showing the operations areas in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out in real mission, but the British army has only recently been loading these videos.
The Americans make recruitment a little different by using the American's Army shooting game for free. In this game the player can directly replace the soldiers in a more or less real simulation.
