The forces of the Mega Strike gather
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will, on Friday, constitute their strike committee, which will be responsible for coordinating the indefinite strike on Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and the strike will begin on Monday, on the day of the final vote on the Health Cash Act.
This action will certainly cause significant stops in traffic as rail traffic will be almost completely stopped and BKV employees (Common Transport Society) will also strike until 1 p.m.
The unions of the League will announce, on Friday afternoon, details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The LIGA - MOSZ strike committee will also be set up as a coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protests will be held and, from Monday, the organizations joining the strike will stop the work for an indefinite period if they are unable to reach agreement with the Government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in Parliament on the Health Cash Act, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the Health Insurance Act, the trade unions will immediately withdraw the appeal to strike.
On the other hand, if the law is voted, the strike committees will meet and decide what action to take.
According to the Monday agenda of the National Assembly, it is likely that the vote on the Health Cash Act will take place only late in the evening or even in the night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, there are important stops in traffic: railways will stop work for an indefinite period and in the morning part of the public transport in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points of the country, half of the road will also be blocked.
Many unions and civil organizations have joined the strike call, and the list of them is constantly updated on the League site.
Some organizations report to strike for an indefinite period of time, while others have declared a temporary cessation of work.
Until Thursday afternoon, the MÁV (Hungarian Iron Chemistry) and the Free Trailer Syndicat (VDSZSZ) have failed to reach agreement on minimum services, and more and more are taking the train.
According to current communications, public transport in Budapest will strike from service beginning until 1 p.m., Budapest airport between 7 p.m. and 9 p.m. in the morning, the Industrial Electricity and Thermal Energy Unions of the League will strike four hours, the Teachers' Syndicat and the Democratic Teachers' Syndicat have called for strike for two hours and from 2 to 8 hours respectively.
The National Medical Association will strike throughout the country in alternance, the Health and Social Sector Employees' Syndicat (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will strike a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four claims made by the League is that the government should withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new concept to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new pension calculation method to be introduced from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim seeks a pre-legal retirement guarantee that would allow the system to transfer the functions that it deserves before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Railway Union (VDSZSZ), attached to the League Union, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economics and Transport concerning secondary railways and the waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard has increased country risk
According to the Policy Capital Risk Analysis Division (Risk Analysing Division), the activity of the Hungarian Guard, established last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Moving for Better Hungary), in several ways increases the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning", society notes that, in connection with the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic confrontations may occur as a result of the exacerbation of the already existing ethnic tension between the Zigean and non-Zigean population of Hungary".
The Research Institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy to probably cause this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the major shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: "public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma case to representatives of radical and extreme political groups that have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Tsigans and the Hungarians."
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are being strengthened and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the Research Institute, with the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular with regard to the confidence in the country's stability and democratic maturity".
They recall that, as a result of a greater publicity given to the reorganization of Hungarian radical and extreme right-wing groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 calling themselves the "National Self-Defense Association".
"The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their members for defence missions (disasters, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, in addition, by referring to the inability of the police, the army, i.e. the state," they added.
They reported that everything was done in accordance with the method that, based on the driver of the political society and the parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions from a civil point of view.
The focus on civility and association status therefore only serves to avoid the legal traps of registration of these associations in court, but they also constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk of neighbouring relations.
