A Heavy Memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the destiny of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archive documents stored on 27 km linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were only available for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. in an individual and nominative manner, at the request of an old victim or of his rights.
The eleven States responsible for their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research "in particular on the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the health of forced workers," says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICCR).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, objected to the openness of these nominative documents to the public due to the sensitivity of certain information.
Like supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The registers of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after war for a practical purpose: to retrieve civilians deported or subjected to compulsory work and, if necessary, to provide evidence of internally, in order to open the way for compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, over 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Dr. Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Research Centre on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
