Data from the European ship in orbit have shown that the planet is certainly twice as small as the Earth, contrary to what was previously thought.
Venus is the nearest planet to Earth.
These two worlds are almost the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus could have had conditions similar to those of the Earth, and could even have been living.
But the greenhouse effect due to carbon dioxide, the air erosion due to solar radiation associated with slower rotation led Venus to another kind of evolution.
Today the planet is deprived of water, is destroyed by hurricanes and lightning storms and has a temperature surface that is warm enough to melt lead.
The discoveries of Venus Express, the European Space Agency's probe, which studied the planet for a year, offer a sad vision of the Earth's potential future due to catastrophic climate changes.
The professor of the Oxford University Department of Physics, Fred Taylor, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "We are beginning to understand why the climate of Venus is so different from that of the Earth, although the planets themselves are virtually similar.
"Our new data allow us to establish a scenario that billions of years ago, Venus would have been originally identical to the Earth, even with a living surface."
