Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we believed so far: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind sparks at the poles, similar to those that appear on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists assume that there are lightning on Venus.
The European "Venus Express" probe has proved this today - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: the lightning on Venus shines at about 56 kilometres of cloud cloud height, reports Christopher Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous cyprin theory, the lightning would have shown life on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, a cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If life has been, it must have been at a very old date of history," explains Sean Solomon from the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there should be little living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times thicker than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the infernal twin of the Earth, but it remains a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to the Earth in mass and dimensions, has been hit by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The start of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venice's research, since no probe was on the way for the exploration of this planet since the 1990s.
According to the researchers, the latest research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" not only highlight Venus' singularity within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighbouring planet are more than expected at first.
Thus, in addition to the already known windstorms at the North Pole, researchers found a cloudstorm at the South Pole, which is going much faster.
The phenomenon recalls air flows in the earthly hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometres, almost as large.
The planet qualified as a star in the evening or morning turns around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns far slower on itself: one Venetian day lasts 243 days on earth.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly reminds the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets have been formed under similar conditions.
Of both, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has been fixed on Earth as carbonate, it is the largest part of the atmosphere on Venus.
