These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Whoever links the concepts of Sweden and wooden box, thinks about Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Isn't that right?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden throw shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxs of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeiting.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" had doubted the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxs of 1968 in Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museum and Stockholm today resulted in a disinspiring result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", the former director of the Pontus Hulten Museum gave a gift to the Moderna Museum in 1995, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm", which are circulating on the international art market.
The old history is overwhelmed, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created its first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes in New York, based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powder soap boxes.
An exhibition of her work at Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - presented hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not artworks, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exposed to Moderna Museet.
Today, witnesses of the time are talking about about about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered right into the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum wrongly claimed that later than about 100 wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have surrendered to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén boxes were produced in Malmö only in 1990, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that date Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Byström, chief Conservator of the Moderna Museum, examined, next to the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three other private Swedish collections, including two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their stratified panels were first printed and pressed, and then applied with a brush of white oil painting.
On the contrary, the texture of the copies dating from 1990 reveals that the painting was directly applied without a layer of background on the stratified panels, using a paint roll - moreover, it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not take another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exposure material."
Already in July, the Authentication Board, of course, announced that it would investigate the "safe accusations" that will be raised in the case of powder soap boxes.
But since then we've been out there with an inexorable silence.
